==============================================================
CIRCULAR LINKED LIST NOTES
==============================================================

1) What is a Circular Linked List?
--------------------------------------------------------------
- A circular linked list is a linked list where
  the last node does not point to null.
- Instead, the last node points back to the first node.

Diagram:
head
 |
 v
[10] -> [20] -> [30]
 ^               |
 |_______________|

--------------------------------------------------------------

2) Main Idea
--------------------------------------------------------------
- In normal singly linked list:
  last.next = null

- In circular linked list:
  last.next = head

- So the list forms a circle.

--------------------------------------------------------------

3) Important Property
--------------------------------------------------------------
- There is no null at the end.
- Traversal can continue forever if we do not stop manually.
- We usually stop when we come back to head.

--------------------------------------------------------------

4) Head and Tail
--------------------------------------------------------------
- head is the first node
- tail is the last node

Important:
- tail.next always points to head

Diagram:
head                 tail
 |                    |
 v                    v
[10] -> [20] -> [30]
 ^___________________|

--------------------------------------------------------------

5) Traversal in Circular Linked List
--------------------------------------------------------------
- Start from head
- Visit nodes one by one
- Stop when current becomes head again

Example:
head
 |
 v
[1] -> [2] -> [3]
 ^______________|

Traversal:
1 -> 2 -> 3

--------------------------------------------------------------

6) Why Circular Linked List is Useful
--------------------------------------------------------------
- Useful when data needs repeated cyclic traversal
- Used in round robin scheduling
- Used in music playlist looping
- Used in turn-based games

--------------------------------------------------------------

7) Insertion Idea
--------------------------------------------------------------
At end:
- new node should point to head
- old tail should point to new node

Example:

Before:
head
 |
 v
[10] -> [20] -> [30]
 ^__________________|

Insert 40

After:
head
 |
 v
[10] -> [20] -> [30] -> [40]
 ^___________________________|

--------------------------------------------------------------

8) Deletion Idea
--------------------------------------------------------------
- While deleting, circle must remain connected
- If deleting head, tail.next should be updated to new head

Example:
head
 |
 v
[10] -> [20] -> [30]
 ^__________________|

Delete 10

After:
head
 |
 v
[20] -> [30]
 ^__________|

--------------------------------------------------------------

9) Advantages of Circular Linked List
--------------------------------------------------------------
- No need to restart traversal from beginning
- Good for cyclic processes
- Tail can quickly connect back to head

--------------------------------------------------------------

10) Disadvantages of Circular Linked List
--------------------------------------------------------------
- Traversal logic is a little tricky
- Risk of infinite loop
- Careful stopping condition is needed

--------------------------------------------------------------

11) Time Complexity
--------------------------------------------------------------
Operation                  Time
--------------------------------------------------------------
Traversal                  O(n)
Insert at beginning        O(n)   // O(1) if tail maintained
Insert at end              O(n)   // O(1) if tail maintained
Delete                     O(n)

--------------------------------------------------------------

12) Real Interview One-Liner
--------------------------------------------------------------
A circular linked list is a linked list in which
the last node points back to the head node,
forming a circle instead of ending with null.

--------------------------------------------------------------

13) Very Short Revision Note
--------------------------------------------------------------
- last node points to head
- no null at end
- forms a circle
- traversal stops when we reach head again
- useful in cyclic problems

--------------------------------------------------------------

